cians in Cuba, Senegal, India, Ghana, and Indone- ~_ sia, worked on computer music at IRCAM,3 and taught through grassroots ; community residencies as well as in universities. 5 ii In 1996, Coleman took one of his groups, the Mystic Rhythm Society, to Cuba, where they collaborated with AfroCuba dc Matanzas. Led since 1957 by Francisco Zamora Chirino, AfroCuba dc Matanzas performs a wide range of folkloric music and dance from the main Afrocuban subcul- V gtures, including LUCHIDI4 (Yoruba), Ar-are (Dahomey), Abakua and Bantu f(Cong0), as well as secular rumba genres. The two groups of musicians I and dancers worked together for two weeks, performing at the Havana Elazz Festival and recording a compact disc. ‘In this essay, I focus on this collaboration in order to develop a number" ;
